ildren and werewolves as portrayed in different media and genres. We begin with the wolf itself as it has been interpreted as a cultural symbol and how it figures in contemporary debates about wilderness and nature. Alongside this, we consider eighteenth-century debates about wild children ­– often thought to have been raised by wolves and other animals – and their role in key questions about the origins of language and society. The collection continues with essays on werewolves and other shapeshifters as depicted in folk tales, literature, film and TV, concluding with the transition from animal to human in contemporary art, poetry and fashion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeral children in literature. 0aMetamorphosis in literature. 0aShapeshifting. 0aWerewolves in literature. 0aWolves in literature. 4aGothic 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aWerewolves.  aanimality.  ashapeshifters.  awild children.  awolves.1 aAbbott, Stacey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmador, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtkin, Polly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrawford, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranck, Kaja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorge, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorge, Sam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHughes, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Bill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLangworthy, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarvin, Garry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab